    combTMB:Combined Models using Template Model Builder

    Deoclecio J. Amorim - deocleciojardim@usp.br, ESALQ-USP

    The combTMB is an R package that implements an extended random effects approach to model repeated, overdispersed binary and count data (called combined models). Furthermore, fit linear and generalized linear mixed. The adjustment of the models is done by maximum likelihood with TMB (Template Model Builder). A common application is for superdispersed and correlated longitudinal data. See Molenberghs, G., Verbeke, G. and Demetrio, C.G. (2007) doi:10.1007/s10985-007-9064-y and Molenberghs et al. (2012) doi:10.1016/j.jmva.2012.05.005.

    Joint work with Afrânio Márcio Corrêa Vieira and Clarice G.B. Demétrio.

    Installation

    Assuming you have a C++ compiler installed, you can install the development version of combTMB like so:

    # install.packages("remotes")
remotes::install_github("deoclecioamorim/combTMB", dependencies = TRUE)

    Basic use

    The syntax of combTMB is very similar to the lme4 and glmmTMB packages. The main function is combTMB(...).

    library(combTMB)
#> Package 'combTMB' version 0.0.0.9000
#> Type 'citation("combTMB")' for citing this R package in publications.
# Poisson-Normal model --------------------------------------------------------
m1 <- combTMB(OT ~ Period+(1|Donor), family=poisson(), data=embryos)
summary(m1)

#> Link function: log 
#> Formula: OT ~ Period + (1 | Donor) 
#> Number of obs: 1148 
#> -2 x logLik         AIC         BIC    df.resid

#>

    Currently, the methods implemented for "combTMB" objects are

    methods(class = "combTMB")
#>  [1] anova        coefDisp     df.residual  dispersion   family      
#>  [6] fitted       formula      getME        logLik       model.frame 
#> [11] model.matrix nobs         partvar      predict      print       
#> [16] ranef        residuals    simulate     summary      terms       
#> [21] vcov        
#> see '?methods' for accessing help and source code
